The second course in a four-part calculus sequence, Math 114 covers multivariable calculus, partial derivatives, first and second order differential equations, vectors, and analytic geometry, with a focus on applications to the physical sciences. &#8232;&#8232;

Catering to students pursuing study in the natural sciences, engineering and economics, Math 114 prepares students for more advanced calculus, whereas Math 115 delves more into probability and matrices for students in the biological and health sciences. Math 114 fulfills the formal reasoning requirement for the College. This course works with the textbook “Calculus” by Stewart.

Students were not happy with Professor Powers’ communication skills. Many simply did not understand the material due to his teaching style. One student explained, “It is often nearly impossible to follow his thought process as he goes over the lesson.” The organization of the course was so poor that “it was rarely clear what topic he was teaching.” Several students said they found it more useful to study from the book and practice exams. One student summarized, “The amount of students that attend class has drastically dropped due to his inability to communicate and simplify the material.” A couple of students said this was the worst class they have taken at Penn.&#8232;&#8232;

Students also took issue with the grading of the exams, particularly with inconsistent partial credit policies.
